span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/4/01 12:38:29 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> Well this one is on shading my CGs, I noticed in many comics and specially in various animes that sometimes the colorist let his/her ship drift a bit too far, I mean that some of the characters look over shadowed with no aparent light sources to justify the massive shading. Am I wrong, or it's just an artistic bit from those guys / gals ?<br>
<br>
If so, when should I apply heavy shadowing to my CGs and when shouldn't I? or Should I justify the shadows in the composition adding light sources or light shading?<br>
<br>
If any of the terms are incorrect please let me know, and tell me the right names OK? Thanx again... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=demonsword1>demonsword1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/4/01 4:29:57 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://demonsword.home.mindspring.com/portfolio/self%20portrait%20(small).gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> It all depends on style and situation.<br>
Extreme values of lights and/or darks in an image can be used to accentuate emotion, action, or a simple, but timely, affectation of response in a viewer.  <br>
The trick is to not over-do it.  To many powerful shadows, or passionate light contrasts can kill your images as easy as save them.  Dynamic shading is just another tool to master when you tell a story in your pictures… ideally, not something to be overdone, or used to hide artistic weaknesses… although maybe an occasional mistake.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p>______________________

http://demonsword.home.mindspring.com/</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/urtagent5.showPublicProfile?language=EN>rtagent5</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/4/01 6:25:41 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://albums.photopoint.com/j/View?u=1653076&a=12656565&p=49816853&Sequence=0&res=high WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> Get a book called drawing dynamic comics it cost 20 bucks at barnes &amp; nobels but it'll teach you every thing about proportions &amp; SHADING that you'll need, &amp; comics really do show light sources, there just not all obvious at first. <p>:evil You know too much, now I guess I'll have to kill you. :evil</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/u7ate9.showPublicProfile?language=EN>7 Ate 9</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/5/01 1:07:25 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> OT, you should keep all of your questions in one post. You seem to have like 4 threads going.<br>
<br>
Anyway, you should use deep shadows when you want to be dramatic, or evil. If you want it to be happy, don't make the shadows as deep. <p>It's true, no man is an island.

A couple of dead guys roped together makes a pretty good raft, though.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufutura2001.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Futura2001</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/5/01 9:06:58 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://home.att.net/~polysin/Futura_Copy.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> I disagree with that, 7 ate 9, it is about how you shade the eyes that determines whether a person looks happy, if you have a lot of shaows on the eyes, it adds an ominous look, but if the eye is lightly shaded and the rest of the face is heavily shaded, the portrait will still look happy.  That is why a drawing done to look like it is in a dark room can look happy, and seductive.  Fin. <p>I looked to the future and I looked to the past, One in the middle and one in last.
One is what I've been and one is what I'll become, I looked at time and it made my soul numb.
If you mess with me you'll get one through the eye and one through lip, and all the while coming from the hip.             ~Futura2001~
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/u7ate9.showPublicProfile?language=EN>7 Ate 9</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/5/01 10:08:50 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> I meant as in the enviroment and such. If you're drawing a monster, you use deep shadows. But if you're drawing a happy outdoor scene, the shadows aren't as deep. Shadows are used for drama. <p>It's true, no man is an island.

A couple of dead guys roped together makes a pretty good raft, though.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ushousetsu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shousetsu</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/psicon.gif width=13 height=13 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/5/01 10:20:15 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/photo.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> the trick is to not have to use colors to do emotions. The masters know how to get emotion across with out the aid of any kind of color scheme, they keep the lighting cosistent and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  right</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> so it doesnt mess up their atmosphere. To get emotion they use everything from the forms of the face and body position, to composition, like how they place the person into the light. No amount of bright eyes or dramatic shading will change emotion, it will just make your person look like a freak if it isnt going along with the actual lighting of the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
You dont put a guy in normal lighting with dramatic shadows just to show hes angry, that would be wrong. If your dealing with normal lighting then leave the emotion up to the face and body position. <p><a href="http://www.newelysium.com"><img src="http://www.newelysium.com/banners/newelysium4.gif" border=0></a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ushousetsu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shousetsu</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/psicon.gif width=13 height=13 BORDER=0> at: 6/5/01 10:22:19 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/u7ate9.showPublicProfile?language=EN>7 Ate 9</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/6/01 7:19:07 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The CG shading and the real shading</span><hr size=1> Thanx Shoutsu, for clearing that up. I was thinking more of pinup art, where you can get the enviroment to match his emotions.<br>
